<h2 class="style1">Sidewalks in San Francisco</h2>
<p class="style1">&nbsp;</p>
<p><span id="_ctl0_leftColumn" class="style1">Department of Public Work (DPW) is responsible 
for repairing defects on most of the city&#39;s streets and sidewalks. </span>
<span id="_ctl0_leftColumn0"><span class="style1">The
<a href="http://www.sfdpw.org/index.aspx?page=642">Sidewalk Inspection and 
Repair Program</a> makes it easier and less expensive for property owners to 
comply with <a href="http://www.sfdpw.org/index.aspx?page=643">City and State 
codes</a> that require them to keep their sidewalks free of defects. </span> </span>
</p>
<p><span id="_ctl0_leftColumn1" class="style1">About 90 percent of all City streets are swept 
mechanically. DPW sweeps more than 150,000 curb miles and removes 24,000 tons of 
litter and debris from San Francisco&#39;s streets annually. </span>
<portlet:actionURL var="defineGoogleMapURL">
</portlet:actionURL>
</p>
<p class="style1">Please provide the following information with your service request:</p>
<ul>
	<li>
	<p class="style1">Location where service is needed (address or intersection)</p>
	</li>
	<li>
	<p class="style1">Type of defect (pothole, crack in pavement, sewers, etc.)</p>
	</li>
</ul>





